#. ¬ß2: `B`
#. ¬ß3: `‚ÜĒ`
#. ¬ß4: `A ‚ÜĒ B`
#. ¬ß5: `constructor`
#. ¬ß6: `A ‚Üí B`
#. ¬ß7: `B ‚Üí A`
#. ¬ß8: `‚ÜĒ`
#. ¬ß9: `h : A ‚ÜĒ B`
#. ¬ß10: `obtain ‚ü®h‚āĀ, h‚āā‚ü© := h`
#. ¬ß11: `h‚āĀ : A ‚Üí B`
#. ¬ß12: `h‚āā : B ‚Üí A`
#. ¬ß13: `h.mp`
#. ¬ß14: `h.mpr`
#. ¬ß15: `mp`
#: Game.Doc.Definition
msgid ""
"¬ß0 means that statements ¬ß1 and ¬ß2 are logically equivalent (‚Äúif and only "
"if‚ÄĚ).\n"
"\n"
"## ¬ß3 as proof target\n"
"\n"
"To show ¬ß4, you can, for example, call ¬ß5\n"
"and then prove ¬ß6 and ¬ß7 separately.\n"
"\n"
"## ¬ß8 as an assumption\n"
"\n"
"You can break down an assumption of the form ¬ß9 using ¬ß10 into its two "
"components\n"
"¬ß11 and ¬ß12.\n"
"However, you can also refer directly to these components with ¬ß13 and ¬ß14.\n"
"(The abbreviation ¬ß15 stands for ‚Äúmodus ponens‚ÄĚ.)"
msgstr ""
