#. ```
#. ¬ß4: `linarith`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"The tactic ¬ß0 can show that a linear equation or inequality follows from "
"given equations or inequalities.\n"
"It is quite flexible and works just as well in ‚Ąē as in ‚ĄĚ.\n"
"However, the (in)equations must be given individually, not logically "
"linked.\n"
"An assumption of the form\n"
"¬ß1\n"
"must first be rewritten with\n"
"¬ß2\n"
"to\n"
"¬ß3\n"
"so that ¬ß4 can do something with it."
msgstr ""
"The tactic ¬ß0 can prove that a linear equation or inequality follows from "
"given equations or inequalities. It is quite flexible and works just as well "
"in ‚Ąē as in ‚ĄĚ. However, each equation or inequality must be must stated "
"separately, not combined with logical operators.\n"
"For example, an assumption of the form \n"
"¬ß1\n"
"must first be rewritten with \n"
"¬ß2\n"
"into\n"
"¬ß3\n"
"in order for ¬ß4 to understand what's going on."

#. ¬ß0: `omega`
#. ¬ß1: `‚Ąē`
#. ¬ß2: `‚Ą§`
#. ¬ß3: `linarith`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"The tactic ¬ß0 can show that a linear equation or inequality in ¬ß1 or ¬ß2\n"
"follows from given equations or inequalities.\n"
"Unlike ¬ß3, it can also handle logical connections between (in)equations."
msgstr ""
"The tactic ¬ß0 can show that a linear equation or inequality in ¬ß1 or ¬ß2 "
"follows from all given equations or inequalities. Unlike ¬ß3, it can also "
"handle logical connectors."

#. ¬ß0: `contrapose`
