#. ¬ß7: ```
#. A ‚ą® ¬¨A
#. ```
#. ¬ß8: `tauto`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With ¬ß0, you can generalize a proof goal\n"
"in the hope that a higher level of abstraction will allow for a simpler "
"proof.\n"
"More precisely, ¬ß1 replaces all occurrences of ¬ß2 in the proof goal with ¬ß3\n"
"(and adds the assumption ¬ß4).\n"
"\n"
"## Example\n"
"\n"
"A goal of the form\n"
"¬ß5\n"
"can be converted with\n"
"¬ß6\n"
"into\n"
"¬ß7\n"
"(and then simply proven with ¬ß8)."
msgstr ""
"With ¬ß0, you can generalise a proof target ‚Äď sometimes a higher degree of "
"abstraction will allow for a simpler proof. More precisely, ¬ß1 replaces all "
"occurrences of ¬ß2 in the proof target with ¬ß3 (and adds the assumption ¬ß4).\n"
"\n"
"## Example \n"
"\n"
"A goal of the form\n"
"¬ß5\n"
"can be converted to\n"
"¬ß7\n"
"using\n"
"¬ß6\n"
"(and then simply proven using ¬ß8)."

#. ¬ß0: `decide`
#. ¬ß1: `True`
#. ¬ß2: `Even 4`
#. ¬ß3: `2 ‚Č§ 5`
#. ¬ß4: `4 ‚Č† 6`
#. ¬ß5: `Prime 7`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With ¬ß0, you can prove statements that can be decided using a simple "
"algorithm.\n"
"These include, in particular, ¬ß1 and statements about concrete numbers such "
"as:\n"
"- ¬ß2\n"
"- ¬ß3\n"
"- ¬ß4\n"
"- ¬ß5"
msgstr ""
"The tactic ¬ß0 can prove true statements for which a decision algorithm "
"exists (and is implemented). These include, in particular, ¬ß1 and statements "
"about specific numbers such as: \n"
"* ¬ß2 \n"
"* ¬ß3 \n"
"* ¬ß4 \n"
"* ¬ß5"

#. ¬ß0: `unfold F`
#. ¬ß1: `F`
#. ¬ß2: `unfold F at h`
#. ¬ß3: `h`
#. ¬ß4: `unfold`
#. ¬ß5: `push_neg`
#. ¬ß6: `rw`
#. ¬ß7: `unfold F`
#. ¬ß8: `simp only [F]`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With ¬ß0, you can write out the definition ¬ß1 in the proof goal.\n"
"With ¬ß2, you do the same thing, but in the assumption ¬ß3.\n"
"\n"
"Although the proof goal or assumption before and after ¬ß4 are identical in "
"definition,\n"
"many tactics (e.g., ¬ß5 or ¬ß6) operate on a syntactic level;\n"
"they do not ‚Äúsee through definitions.‚ÄĚ\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and Relatives\n"
"\n"
"The tactics ¬ß7 and ¬ß8 do practically the same thing."
msgstr ""
"With ¬ß0, you can spell out the definition ¬ß1 in the goal.\n"
"With ¬ß2, you do the same in assumption ¬ß3. \n"
"\n"
"Goal and assumption before and after ¬ß4 are definitionally equivalent, but "
"tactics such as ¬ß5 or ¬ß6 operate on a syntactic level ‚Äď they do not ‚Äúsee "
"through‚ÄĚ definitions. It can easily happen that they work only after (or "
"only before) an ¬ß4.\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relations\n"
"\n"
"For all practical purposes, ¬ß7 is equivalent to ¬ß8."

#. ¬ß0: `trans`
#. ¬ß1: `‚äĘ A = C`
#. ¬ß2: `trans B`
#. ¬ß3: `‚äĘ A = B`
#. ¬ß4: `‚äĘ B = C`
#. ¬ß5: `‚äĘ A ‚ÜĒ C`
#. ¬ß6: `trans B`
#. ¬ß7: `‚äĘ A ‚ÜĒ B`
#. ¬ß8: `‚äĘ B ‚ÜĒ C`
#. ¬ß9: `A = B‚āĀ = B‚āā = B‚āÉ ‚Ä¶ = C`
#. ¬ß10: `calc`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With ¬ß0, you insert an intermediate step into an equation or equivalence.\n"
"\n"
"| before | tactic    | after                |\n"
"|:------------ |:--------- |:----------------------- |\n"
"| ¬ß1    | ¬ß2 | ¬ß3 and ¬ß4 |\n"
"| ¬ß5    | ¬ß6 | ¬ß7 and ¬ß8 |\n"
"\n"
"Since you can repeat the tactic several times, it is suitable for\n"
"performing a ‚Äúcalculation‚ÄĚ ¬ß9 step by step.\n"
"\n"
"(Outside of the game, however, the multi-line tactic ¬ß10 is better suited "
"for such calculations.)"
msgstr ""
"With ¬ß0, you insert an intermediate step into an equation or equivalence. \n"
"\n"
"| before | tactic | after | \n"
"|:------------ |:--------- |:-----------------------| \n"
"| ¬ß1 | ¬ß2 | ¬ß3 and ¬ß4 | \n"
"| ¬ß5 | ¬ß6 | ¬ß7 and ¬ß8 | \n"
"\n"
"By repeating this tactic several times, you can perform a step-by-step "
"‚Äúcalculation‚ÄĚ ¬ß9. \n"
"\n"
"(Outside of this game, however, the multi-line tactic ¬ß10 is better suited "
"for such calculations.)"

#. ¬ß0: `suffices h : P`
#. ¬ß1: `P`
#. ¬ß2: `P`
#. ¬ß3: `have h : P`
#. ¬ß4: `P`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With ¬ß0, you introduce a proof section in which you show\n"
"that the desired proof goal follows from ¬ß1.\n"
"Then you prove ¬ß2.\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives\n"
"¬ß3 works the same way, except that you must first prove ¬ß4 before you can\n"
"continue with the main proof."
msgstr ""
"With ¬ß0, you start arguing that the desired goal follows from ¬ß1. Once that "
"argument is complete, you prove ¬ß2. \n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relations \n"
"\n"
"¬ß3 works in exactly the same way, except that you must first prove ¬ß4 before "
"you can continue with the main proof."

#. ¬ß0: `have h : P`
#. ¬ß1: `suffices h : P`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With ¬ß0, you introduce an intermediate result.\n"
"You must then prove this intermediate result\n"
"before you can continue with the actual proof.\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives\n"
"¬ß1 works in exactly the same way, except that you can continue with the main "
"proof first and\n"
"only have to prove your intermediate result at the very end."
msgstr ""
"With ¬ß0, you introduce an intermediate result. You must then prove this "
"intermediate result before you can continue with the actual proof. \n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relations \n"
"\n"
"¬ß1 works in exactly the same way, except that you can continue with the main "
"proof first and only have to prove your intermediate result at the very end."

#. ¬ß0: `specialize h a‚āĀ a‚āā`
#. ¬ß1: `have h := h a‚āĀ a‚āā`
#. ¬ß2: `h : ‚ąÄ m‚āĀ m‚āā, P m‚āĀ m‚āā`
#. ¬ß3: `h : P a‚āĀ a‚āā`
#. ¬ß4: `specialize`
#. ¬ß5: `have`
#. ¬ß6: `specialize h ‚Ä¶`
#. ¬ß7: `h`
#. ¬ß8: `h`
#. ¬ß9: ```
#. have ha := h a‚āĀ a‚āā
#. have hb := h b‚āĀ b‚āā
#. ```
#. ¬ß10: ```
#. h : ‚ąÄ m‚āĀ m‚āā, P m‚āĀ m‚āā
#. ha : P a‚āĀ a‚āā
#. hb : P b‚āĀ b‚āā
#. ```
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"¬ß0 is equivalent to ¬ß1: the tactic replaces an assumption\n"
"¬ß2 with the special case ¬ß3.\n"
"\n"
"If you want to specialize multiple times, instead of ¬ß4 you should use ¬ß5,\n"
"since ¬ß6 overwrites the old assumption ¬ß7.\n"
"From the above assumption ¬ß8, you can obtain the following three assumptions "
"with\n"
"¬ß9\n"
":\n"
"¬ß10"
msgstr ""
"¬ß0 is equivalent to ¬ß1: \n"
"the tactic replaces the assumption ¬ß2 with the special case ¬ß3. \n"
"\n"
"If you want to specialise multiple times, you should use ¬ß5 instead of ¬ß4, "
"as ¬ß6 overwrites the old assumption ¬ß7. For example, you could apply \n"
"¬ß9\n"
"to the above assumption ¬ß8 to end up with the following three assumptions:\n"
"¬ß10"

#: Game.Levels.Babylon
msgid "Babylon"
msgstr "Babylon"

#: Game.Levels.Babylon
msgid "Intro Babylon"
msgstr ""
"You find yourself on a planet where countless stone slabs are stacked into "
"bizarrely tall towers. The entire landscape looks like a giant 3D puzzle, "
"with each slab neatly stacked on top of the ones below. Some towers are so "
"tall that they seem to disappear into the sky. Soon you encounter the first "
"inhabitant of this planet.\n"
"\n"
"**Babylonian**: Welcome to *Babylon*! \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Oh ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"Now you're nervous.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: Are you sure these towers are stable? \n"
"\n"
"**Babylonian**: Absolutely! \n"
"\n"
"**You**: How do you build these masterpieces? \n"
"\n"
"**Babylonian**: Very simple. One stone at a time."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L01_Sum_Simp_Card
msgid "Conclusion Babylon L01"
msgstr "**Babylonian**: Looks good!"

#. ¬ß0: $( \\sum_{i\\in I} 1)$
#. ¬ß1: $I$
#. ¬ß2: $I$
#. ¬ß3: `simp`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L01_Sum_Simp_Card
msgid ""
"Explain goal as ¬ß0 being equal to the number of elements in ¬ß1\n"
"i.e. the cardinality of ¬ß2. Try ¬ß3"
msgstr ""
"**You**: That's quite a lot of new stuff ‚Ä¶ let me see ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"This looks like ¬ß0 is equal to ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: ‚Ä¶ the number of elements in ¬ß1, i.e. the cardinality of ¬ß2. \n"
"\n"
"**Babylonian**: And can you prove that? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble** *(to you)*: I would try ¬ß3 first. That can be a really powerful "
"tactic."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L01_Sum_Simp_Card
msgid "Intro Babylon L01"
msgstr ""
"**Babylonian**: Each tower has an inscription. It tells you exactly why the "
"tower is standing the way it's standing. Here, for example."

