#. ¬ß0: `simp`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L02_Card2
msgid "Again try using ¬ß0"
msgstr "**You**: ¬ß0 again?"

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L02_Card2
msgid "Intro Babylon L02"
msgstr "You go over to the next tower."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L03_sum_congr
msgid "Intro Babylon L03"
msgstr ""
"Next, you come to an empty building site that appears to have been inactive "
"for a long time. The construction sign reads:"

#. ¬ß0: $I \\subseteq \\{-1,0,1\\}$
#. ¬ß1: `trans ‚ąĎ i ‚ąą I, 0`
#. ¬ß2: `\\sum`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L03_sum_congr
msgid ""
"Remind that goal looks like ¬ß0. Try ¬ß1. The sum sign is written\n"
"as ¬ß2."
msgstr ""
"**You**: The assumption looks like a convoluted version of ¬ß0. Either way, "
"it can't be a large sum. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No. But we probably need an intermediate step to get the "
"specified result. I suggest: ¬ß1. You can write the sum sign as ¬ß2."

#. ¬ß0: `apply sum_congr`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L03_sum_congr
msgid "try ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Exactly. Now you can write ¬ß0 ‚Äď if two indexed sums have "
"identical index sets, and if the individual expressions being summed up are "
"also equal, then the sums themselves are equal."

#. ¬ß0: $¬ę{i}¬Ľ=0$
#. ¬ß1: $¬ę{i}¬Ľ=1$
#. ¬ß2: $¬ę{i}¬Ľ=2$
#. ¬ß3: `have`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "Assumptions have to entail ¬ß0 or ¬ß1 or ¬ß2. Try ¬ß3"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Somehow, the assumptions must imply ¬ß0 or ¬ß1 or ¬ß2. Perhaps "
"you could spell this out explicitly with ¬ß3?"

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "Intro Babylon L04"
msgstr ""
"You continue wandering from tower to tower. Finally, you stop at a tower "
"that seems strange to you. After walking around it once, you realise why: "
"there is no entrance. Eventually, you notice a floor slab with the following "
"inscription."

#. ¬ß0: ``` i ^ 3 - 3 * i ^ 2 + 2 * i = 0 ```
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "Introduce assumptions until ¬ß0 as goal"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: I suggest you first introduce all assumptions, so that the "
"goal has the form:\n"
"¬ß0"

#. ¬ß0: `apply sum_subset`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "Now try out ¬ß0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Good. And now ¬ß0."

#. ¬ß0: $$ \\sum_{i=0}^{n} (i^3 - 3 i^2 + 2 i)  = \\sum_{i=3}^{n} (i^3 - 3 i^2 + 2i) $$
#. ¬ß1: $0$
#. ¬ß2: $i$
#. ¬ß3: `sum_subset`
#. ¬ß4: `I‚āĀ ‚äÜ I‚āā`
#. ¬ß5: `I‚āĀ`
#. ¬ß6: `I‚āā`
#. ¬ß7: `I‚āĀ`
#. ¬ß8: `I‚āā`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid ""
"Remind goal ¬ß0 with ¬ß1 for the value in the sum for fist three ¬ß2. Try ¬ß3: "
"If ¬ß4 and term is disappearing for all elements in ¬ß5 not in ¬ß6, then the "
"sum over ¬ß7 equals sum over ¬ß8"
msgstr ""
"**You**:  Slowly, please. What we need to show is: \n"
"\n"
"¬ß0\n"
"\n"
"Presumably, the expression in the sum is simply ¬ß1 for the first three "
"values of ¬ß2 ‚Ä¶ yes, exactly. Now, how do I formulate this? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: You could use ¬ß3: given ¬ß4, and given an expression in the sum "
"that disappears on all elements of ¬ß5 that are not in ¬ß6, the sum over ¬ß7 is "
"equal to the sum over ¬ß8."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "Show that term in sum is zero for first three indexes"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Great! Now you just have to show what you said earlier: the "
"expression under the sum is zero for the first three indices."

#. ¬ß0: `simp`
#. ¬ß1: `omega`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "Try ¬ß0 & ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: I'm sure some combination of ¬ß0 and ¬ß1 will prove this. That's "
"how we did it on Luna, in any case."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{h}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `obtain`
#. ¬ß2: `obtain h | h | h  := ¬ę{h}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "[Babylon] Split ¬ß0 with ¬ß1: ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Now you can split the assumption ¬ß0 into three cases with ¬ß2."

#. ¬ß0: `Icc_subset_Icc_iff`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "¬ß0 is useful here"
msgstr "**Scribble**: You could definitely use ¬ß0 here."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L05_sum_subset2
msgid "Conclusion Babylon L05"
msgstr "**Babylonians**: Well done!"

#. ¬ß0: `Even.neg_pow`
#. ¬ß1: `Odd.neg_pow`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L05_sum_subset2
msgid "Familiar situation: try ¬ß0 or ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Haven't we already seen some lemmas that might be helpful "
"here? How about ¬ß0 or ¬ß1?"

#. ¬ß0: $$ \\sum_{i \\in I} \\left( (-1)^i + 1 \\right) $$
#. ¬ß1: $I$
#. ¬ß2: $i$
#. ¬ß3: $i$
#. ¬ß4: $2$
#. ¬ß5: `trans`
#. ¬ß6: ``` ‚ąĎ i ‚ąą { i ‚ąą I | Even i}, ((-1)^i + 1) ```
#. ¬ß7: ``` ‚ąĎ i ‚ąą { i ‚ąą I | Even i}, 2 ```
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L05_sum_subset2
msgid ""
"Goal is to show that ¬ß0 is equal to twice the amount of\n"
"even numbers in ¬ß1. Note that sum disappears for uneven ¬ß2. For even ¬ß3 the "
"sum is ¬ß4. Use ¬ß5 to\n"
"constrain sum to ¬ß6 and then use ¬ß7\n"
"as intermediate step."
msgstr ""
"**You**: Now we need to show that ¬ß0 is the same as twice the count of even "
"numbers in ¬ß1. Right? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Right. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: And that's because ‚Ä¶ the expression in the sum disappears for odd "
"¬ß2, and for even ¬ß3 it is equal to ¬ß4. Mmmm ‚Ä¶\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Why don't you introduce a few intermediate steps with ¬ß5 "
"again. First, you want to restrict the sum to the set of even indices, i.e. "
"to: \n"
"¬ß6 \n"
"And then you probably want to use \n"
"¬ß7\n"
"as another intermediate step."

#. ¬ß0: `sum_congr`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L05_sum_subset2
msgid "Now oyu can use ¬ß0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: That looks good. Now you're ready to use ¬ß0 again."

#. ¬ß0: `simp`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L05_sum_subset2
msgid "Try out ¬ß0 again"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Try ¬ß0 again."

#. ¬ß0: `rw`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L06_Induction_sum_insert__arithmetic_sum
msgid "Apply induction hypothesis with ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**You**: And how do I apply the induction hypothesis now? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: With ¬ß0, just as you would with any other assumption."

#. ¬ß0: $[0, ¬ę{d}¬Ľ+1]$
#. ¬ß1: $[0,¬ę{d}¬Ľ]$
#. ¬ß2: $¬ę{d}¬Ľ+1$
#. ¬ß3: `insert_Icc_eq_Icc_add_one_right`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L06_Induction_sum_insert__arithmetic_sum
msgid "Divide interval ¬ß0 into ¬ß1 and ¬ß2 by using ¬ß3"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Now you want to split the interval ¬ß0 over which the sum is "
"taken into ¬ß1 and ¬ß2. You could use the lemma ¬ß3, which we have already seen."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L06_Induction_sum_insert__arithmetic_sum
msgid "Intro Babylon L06"
msgstr ""
"**Babylonian**: Come, let me show you one of our most beautiful towers!\n"
"\n"
"The path leads steeply uphill. The tower at the top is indeed very "
"impressive. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: That must be the famous *Gaussian Tower of Babylon*! I read "
"about this somewhere. \n"
"\n"
"**Babylonian**: Indeed. Gauss was a Babylonian!"

#. ¬ß0: `simp`
#. ¬ß1: `ring`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L06_Induction_sum_insert__arithmetic_sum
msgid "The rest is simple computation solvable by ¬ß0 and ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**You**: From here, it should just be a calculation. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: True. Any combination of ¬ß0 and ¬ß1 should do the trick."

#. ¬ß0: $$ \\sum_{i = 0}^n i = \\tfrac{1}{2} \\cdot n \\cdot (n + 1) $$
#. ¬ß1: `n`
#. ¬ß2: `induction n with d hd`
#. ¬ß3: `with ‚Ä¶`
#. ¬ß4: `d`
#. ¬ß5: `hd`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L06_Induction_sum_insert__arithmetic_sum
msgid ""
"To proof sum ¬ß0\n"
"try to perform induction over ¬ß1 using ¬ß2. ¬ß3 is optional and you can\n"
"decide on the name of your induction variable (¬ß4) and hypothesis (¬ß5)."
msgstr ""
"**You**: I've seen this sum before. \n"
"¬ß0 \n"
"Wasn't there this story about little Gauss coming up with this formula, and "
"with very simple argument why it holds? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: I'm not into that kind of gossip. I would just do an induction "
"over ¬ß1. In Leanish, that would be: ¬ß2!\n"
"\n"
"**You**: Why ¬ß3? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: That part is optional, of course. It allows you to specify "
"names for your induction variable (¬ß4) and hypothesis (¬ß5)."

#. ¬ß0: `simp`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L06_Induction_sum_insert__arithmetic_sum
msgid "You can skip induction start by using ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**You**: First, the base case ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: You can often brush this aside with ¬ß0!"

#. ¬ß0: `sum_insert`
#. ¬ß1: $[0,¬ę{d}¬Ľ]$
#. ¬ß2: $¬ę{d}¬Ľ+1$
#. ¬ß3: `rw [sum_insert]`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L06_Induction_sum_insert__arithmetic_sum
msgid ""
"¬ß0 will divide sum as wished: a sum over ¬ß1 and an additional summand for "
"¬ß2.\n"
"Try ¬ß3"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Exactly! And now ¬ß0 splits the sum exactly as you want it: "
"into a sum over ¬ß1 and then an additional summand for ¬ß2. Try it: ¬ß3"

#. ¬ß0: `rw [sum_insert]`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L07_Induction2_sum_insert2
msgid "And yet again ¬ß0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Exactly, and now again ¬ß0."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L07_Induction2_sum_insert2
msgid "Intro Babylon L07"
msgstr ""
"Right next to the Gaussian Tower there's another empty building site. This "
