msgid ""
"Try ¬ß0 or ¬ß1.\n"
"¬ß2 without ¬ß3 does not work. You must explicitly point out which value\n"
"the variable ¬ß4 should have in statment ¬ß5."
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: You could use ¬ß0 or ¬ß1. (¬ß2 without ¬ß3 does not work here ‚Äď "
"you must explicitly specify the value of the variable ¬ß4 when invoking ¬ß5."

#. ¬ß0: `constructor`
#. ¬ß1: `comp_apply`
#. ¬ß2: `congr_fun`
#: Game.Levels.Epo.L04_RightInverse
msgid "Try ¬ß0, ¬ß1 | ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble:** I would actually start with ¬ß0 again. And then use the usual "
"suspects: ¬ß1, ¬ß2, ‚Ä¶"

#. ¬ß0: `f`
#. ¬ß1: `let g : ‚Ą§ √ó ‚Ą§ ‚Üí ‚Ą§ √ó ‚Ą§ := fun (m, n) ‚Ü¶ ‚Ä¶`
#. ¬ß2: `use g`
#. ¬ß3: `f`
#: Game.Levels.Epo.L05_RightInverse
msgid ""
"Show that there is right inverse to ¬ß0. You could again set mapping ¬ß1\n"
"and then apply ¬ß2. Think how right inverse of ¬ß3 could look like."
msgstr ""
"**You**: So here, I'm supposed to show that ¬ß0 has a right inverse?\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes. You can specify a candidate with ¬ß1 again, then test it "
"with ¬ß2. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Okay. Let me think what a right inverse to ¬ß3 might look like‚Ä¶"

#. ¬ß0: `choose`
#. ¬ß1: `choose`
#. ¬ß2: `choose g hg using nonempty_fibre`
#: Game.Levels.Epo.L06_choose
msgid "Remember ¬ß0. This here is a good setting for ¬ß1. Try ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**You**: That sounds a bit like the axiom of choice. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Bingo! Don't you remember ¬ß0? This is where ¬ß1 really comes "
"into its own. Try ¬ß2."

#: Game.Levels.Epo.L07_SurjectiveRightInverse
msgid "Conclusion Epo L07"
msgstr ""
"You receive a round of applause. \n"
"\n"
"Then you are bid farewell. Unfortunately, you cannot use a transport capsule "
"for the return journey. These only work in one direction. So you have to "
"walk back to the spaceship: first down the stairs, then outside from the "
"office building to the sleeping quarters, and finally up to the roof in a "
"normal lift."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid
msgid "Euklid"
msgstr "Euclid"

#. ¬ß0: `‚ąÜ‚Čö‚Ä≤‚¨ô‚āá‚ľÄ‚Ę¶‚Ĺ™‚Öď‚ęē‚Ĺ≠‚ā†‚ąė‚ĎĮ‚ęā‚Ęź‚ôú‚ćá‚ģČ‚äü‚éß‚∂§‚íć‚Čß‚äü‚ėł‚©č‚á™‚ďÖ‚©ô‚Ė•‚ĶÄ‚ģü‚™≥‚Éé‚ĒĀ‚Ņ©‚Ěź‚†°‚īĚ‚łĎ‚áŹ‚ģČ‚É£‚óĻ‚™Ü‚ĺó‚ľį‚Ēį‚õ¶‚Čá‚ļĚ‚źú‚īä‚¨ü‚ĺĆ‚óä‚Āč‚įć‚Īá‚∑Ą‚§ü‚āĺ‚Ĺ¨‚üĮ‚≥Ė‚ß≠‚äł‚ĶĻ‚ĺö‚Ą°‚ĺĄ‚ĘŹ‚®ä‚ôā‚ľ≠‚†Ľ‚ī≤‚Ą¶‚ģÜ‚ôĒ‚°Ć‚éß‚Čé‚¨Ć‚ćô‚Ēą‚úü‚ĹČ‚āó‚úú‚Čě ‚Ä¶`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid
msgid "Intro Euklid: shows encrypted message ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: This planet looks like a labyrinth. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Or rather like a maze. \n"
"\n"
"You slowly fly closer. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: It's a library! We should definitely take a closer look. But I "
"don't know where to land. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Maybe there?  It looks like a small reading room. Can you manage? \n"
"\n"
"Yes, Scribble can manage. You get off and look around. \n"
"\n"
"The shelves are at least 15 feet high, and densely packed with thick-bound "
"books. You pull one out at random, open a page and read the following: \n"
"\n"
"¬ß0 \n"
"\n"
"**You**:  Scribble, do you have any idea what this is? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: I think Gibberish is the technical term. So no, I have no "
"idea. \n"
"\n"
"You look at a few other books, but they all contain similar gibberish. The "
"books in the aisles are no better. Then you discover a book lying open on "
"the floor."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L01_prod_pos
msgid "Intro Euklid L01"
msgstr "Someone has highlighted the following line:"

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L01_prod_pos
msgid "The expression itself seems to be correct"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: But everything that follows is complete nonsense again. The "
"statement itself is correct, though, I think.  Let's see whether we can "
"prove this."

#. ¬ß0: `‚ąŹ a ‚ąą A, a`
#. ¬ß1: `A`
#. ¬ß2: `apply prod_pos`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L01_prod_pos
msgid "¬ß0 is Leanic for the product over all numbers in ¬ß1. Try ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**You**: This line is actually legible. Surely ¬ß0 is Leanish for the product "
"of all numbers in ¬ß1, right? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes! And the next line makes sense too: ¬ß2."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{h}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid "Disect ¬ß0 into its constituents"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: And now let's break down assumption ¬ß0 into its three "
"components."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{b}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `a`
#. ¬ß2: `intro`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid ""
"Goal: if ¬ß0 divides factor ¬ß1 of a product then it also divides the "
"product.\n"
"Try ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: This line also looks very reasonable: if a number ¬ß0 divides a "
"factor ¬ß1 of a product, then it certainly also divides the entire product.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: But already the first line of the ‚Äúproof‚ÄĚ doesn't make any sense "
"whatsoever. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, it doesn't. But let's again try it ourselves. We'll start "
"with ¬ß2, of course."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid "Intro Euklid L02"
msgstr ""
"A little further down the corridor, you see another book lying open on the "
"floor."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{a}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `insert_erase`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid "Seperate factor ¬ß0 out of product by using ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Presumably, I now want to separate the factor ¬ß0 from the product, "
"somehow? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes, that should help. I think you will need something like ¬ß1."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid "The rest should be easy"
msgstr "**Scribble**: From here, it should be easy."

#. ¬ß0: `rw [‚Üź insert_erase ¬ę{ha}¬Ľ]`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid "Try rewriting with ¬ß0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Try ¬ß0."

#. ¬ß0: `prod_insert`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid "Use ¬ß0 to actually extract the factot"
msgstr "**Scribble**: And now you use ¬ß0 to extract the factor."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid "Conclusion Euklid L03"
msgstr ""
"You walk down a corridor where several books are lying on the floor. But "
"none of them are open. At the next intersection, another corridor branches "
"off with several books scattered on the floor. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Could this be a clue? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Let's follow it!"

#. ¬ß0: `let all_primes := hf.toFinset`
#. ¬ß1: `Finset`
#. ¬ß2: `hf`
#. ¬ß3: `{ p : ‚Ąē | Prime p} : Set ‚Ąē`
#. ¬ß4: `{ p : ‚Ąē | Prime p} : Finset ‚Ąē`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid ""
"Here ¬ß0 is useful. The product over all primes can only be reasoned\n"
"with, when interpreted as a ¬ß1. The first line does exactly this: it uses ¬ß2 "
"to transform\n"
"¬ß3 into a finite set ¬ß4."
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Oh! That actually looks quite interesting: If we assume that "
"there are only finitely many primes, then we can find a positive natural "
"number divisible by each of them. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Yes.  Sounds a little absurd, but correct. And the proof? The first "
"line here is ¬ß0. Does that make any sense?\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: It does indeed! To prove the statement, you probably want to "
"consider the product of all prime numbers. And for that to be syntactically "
"possible, you have to consider this set of all prime numbers as a ¬ß1. The "
"first line does exactly that: it uses the assumption ¬ß2 to turn ¬ß3 into a "
"finite subset ¬ß4.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: Okay, I'll give it a try."

#. ¬ß0: `simp`
#. ¬ß1: `simp`
#. ¬ß2: `all_primes`
#. ¬ß3: `simp [all_primes]`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid ""
"If ¬ß0 alone does not work, try giving ¬ß1\n"
"the definition of ¬ß2. Try ¬ß3"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: If ¬ß0 doesn't work here, you may need to give ¬ß1 the "
"definition of ¬ß2: ¬ß3."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid "Intro Euklid L03"
msgstr ""
"You have to walk quite a bit to find the next open book. Scribble has "
"started rolling out a red thread so that you can find your way back."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid "Try constructor"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Well done! \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Haven't we already proved a few things that would be quite useful "
"now? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Oops. Yes, I guess you're right, but unfortunately, I didn't "
"save them. You'll have to reconstruct the arguments. Sorry!"

#. ¬ß0: `A`
#. ¬ß1: `A : Set T`
#. ¬ß2: `h : Set.Finite A`
#. ¬ß3: `Set.Finite A`
#. ¬ß4: `h.toFinset`
#. ¬ß5: `h.toFinset : Finset T`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid ""
"[Doc.Theorem] Set.Finite.toFinset:\n"
"Given ¬ß0, ¬ß1 with ¬ß2, ¬ß3,\n"
"¬ß4, ¬ß5 is the same subset viewed as finite subset."
msgstr ""
"Given a subset ¬ß1 which is finite by some assumption ¬ß2,\n"
"the expression ¬ß5 denotes the same subset ¬ß0, but now explicitly viewed as a "
"*finite* subset."

#. ¬ß0: `Finset.prod_pos`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid "¬ß0 is helpful here"
msgstr "**Scribble**:  Here, ¬ß0 should help again."

#. ¬ß0: `all_primes.bubblewrap = blister cong foo`
#. ¬ß1: `\\prod`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L03_Finite_toFinset__prod_insert2
msgid ""
"¬ß0 us nonsensical. You want to use the product of\n"
"all those numbers. Write the product sign as ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**You**: And the next line? \n"
"\n"
"¬ß0\n"
"\n"
"Does that still make sense? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, that's complete nonsense again. \n"
"As I said, you probably want to use the product of all these numbers now. \n"
"You can write the product sign as ¬ß1."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L04_Boss_infinitely_many_primes
msgid "Conclusion Euklid L04"
msgstr ""
"Euclid is thrilled and dances around in circles. He doesn't want to let you "
"go. You promise to stay in touch."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L04_Boss_infinitely_many_primes
msgid "Intro Euklid L04"
msgstr ""
"After a while, you hear some paper rustling. Three more corners, and you "
"find yourselves in an office. The plaque on the door reads ‚ÄúEuclid, Director "
"of the Library‚ÄĚ.\n"
"\n"
"**Euclid**: Good day! How nice to see a few visitors here for a change. Had "
"I known *what kind* of library this was, I would never have accepted the "
"position as director.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: What kind of library would you have liked to direct? \n"
"\n"
"**Euclid**: I was promised that I would find, ‚Äúamong other things‚ÄĚ, "
"translations into Leanish of the writings of my famous ancestor. You know, "
"the one from *your* universe. And now I've been searching for years, in the "
"catalogue and on the actual shelves, and I've still only found tiny "
"fragments. Look, I've finally started to formulate one of his results "
"myself. Perhaps you could help me?"

#. ¬ß0: `exists_prime_and_dvd`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L04_Boss_infinitely_many_primes
msgid "Try proof by conradiction. For this employ ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: With pleasure! It's a typical proof by contradiction, isn't "
"it? Assuming there were only finitely many prime numbers, we would find that "
"the product of all prime numbers plus one is not divisible by any prime "
"number. On the other hand, ¬ß0. Contradiction."

#: Game.Levels.Implis
msgid "Implis"
msgstr "Implis"

#. ¬ß0: `tauto`
#: Game.Levels.Implis
msgid "Intro Implis: mention that planet could not be solved without ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"Back on the spaceship, you set off for a neighbouring planet that also "
"appears to be inhabited. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: I still feel that I couldn't have solved Queen Logwynn's problem "
"without ¬ß0. Didn't it involve implications? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Perhaps we'll learn more on *Implis*, the planet we're now "
"heading towards. Hold tight ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"And with that, Scribble begins the landing approach. \n"
"\n"
"Implis appears to be a huge open-cast mine. Conveyor belts criss-cross "
"everywhere, but most of them are halted. \n"
"A shy ‚ÄúHead of Operations‚ÄĚ is waiting for you.\n"
"\n"
"**Head of Operations**: You've come at just the right moment! I've already "
"heard about you. Real mathematicians! You see, we extract truth values here. "
"And you have to be extremely careful. One mistake and everything collapses. "
"I'm very cautious. I always say: downtime over downfall!"

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L01_Intro
msgid "Conclusion Implis L01"
msgstr ""
"**Head of Operations**: Perfect! Thank you very much! \n"
"\n"
"He goes to a control panel and presses a few buttons. \n"
"Somewhere, a conveyor belt creaks loudly and starts moving. \n"
"\n"
"**Head of Operations**: Do you have a few more minutes?"

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ ‚ąß ¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L01_Intro
msgid "Having ¬ß0 and ¬ß1 in your assumptions you have to show ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Okay. So now I have both ¬ß0 and ¬ß1 among my assumptions and need to "
"show ¬ß2. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Exactly. And you already know how to do that."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L01_Intro
msgid "Intro Implis L01"
msgstr "**Head of Operations**: Here, for example:"

#. ¬ß0: `\\to`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß3: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ und ¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß4: `tauto`
#. ¬ß5: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß6: `h`
#. ¬ß7: `intro h`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L01_Intro
msgid ""
"Proof the implication (¬ß0), that assuming ¬ß1 is true, ¬ß2 implies ¬ß3\n"
"is also true. You cannot use ¬ß4. Begin by assumption that ¬ß5 is true. For "
"this choose\n"
"name ¬ß6 for assumption and introduce it via ¬ß7"
msgstr ""
"**Head of Operations**: The workers think this is correct and that we "
"urgently need it. But no one can prove it to me. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: One moment. This *is* an implication (¬ß0) again! We assume that ¬ß1 "
"holds, and we need to show that under this assumption ¬ß2 implies ¬ß3. Well, "
"of course! That's obviously true.\n"
"\n"
"The Head of Operations looks at you expectantly. \n"
"\n"
"**You** *(softly to Scribble)*: Should I write down ¬ß4 for him? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble** *(equally softy)*: The way he looks, I'm afraid he won't "
"understand that either. Better write out the proof.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: But how? I'd like to start by saying something like ‚ÄúSo let's "
"assume that ¬ß5 holds ‚Ä¶‚ÄĚ \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes, good idea. Just choose a name for your assumption, for "
"example ¬ß6 as in ‚Äúhypothesis‚ÄĚ, and start with ¬ß7."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L02_Revert
msgid "Conclusion Implis L02"
msgstr ""
"The Head of Operations gladly accepts your solution and picks up the phone."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L02_Revert
msgid "Intro Implis L02"
msgstr ""
"The Head of Operations takes a stack of paper out of a container. \n"
"\n"
"**Head of Operations**: Quite a lot has accumulated here. It would be really "
"great if you could help me a little more. \n"
"\n"
"He hands you the top sheet."

#. ¬ß0: `mopo`
#. ¬ß1: `mopo`
#. ¬ß2: `revert ¬ę{hA}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L02_Revert
msgid "You cannot use ¬ß0. There is no ¬ß1. Try ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**Head of Operations**: This is from a colleague. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: I'm sure I've read this somewhere before. Wait a minute ‚Ä¶ "
"That's right! \n"
"It was when I was crawling Wikipedia: \n"
"\n"
"*‚ÄúModus ponens is a figure of reasoning already familiar in ancient logic, "
"which is used in many logical ‚Ä¶‚ÄĚ*\n"
"\n"
"**You**: Scribble! We're looking for proof, not a historical essay! \n"
"Or are you trying to tell me that I should write ¬ß1 or something similar? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, sorry, ¬ß1 won't get you anywhere. Try ¬ß2 instead."

#. ¬ß0: `revert`
#. ¬ß1: `intro`
#. ¬ß2: `intro`
#. ¬ß3: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ \\to ¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß4: `revert`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L02_Revert
msgid ""
"¬ß0 is like ¬ß1 'backwards'. ¬ß2 takes the premisse out of ¬ß3\n"
"and makes it into an assumption. ¬ß4 takes an assumption and sets it as the "
"implication premisse\n"
"in front of the goal."
msgstr ""
"**You**: I see. ¬ß0 is basically ¬ß1 in reverse. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Exactly. ¬ß2 takes the premise of an implication ¬ß3 in the goal "
"and turns it into an assumption. ¬ß4, on the other hand, takes an assumption "
"and moves it into the goal as an implication premise. Anyway, let's get this "
"finished now."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L03_Apply
msgid "Conclusion Implis L03"
msgstr "This time, the phone call seems to go well."

#. ¬ß0: `revert`
#. ¬ß1: `revert`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L03_Apply
msgid "Intro Implis L03: This Level does not know ¬ß0. Try proof without ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"Unfortunately, the phone call isn't going so well. He hangs up again and "
