msgstr ""
"**Head of Operations**: Okay, that makes sense. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble** *(to you)*: By the way, just as ¬ß0 has two parts called ¬ß1 and "
"¬ß2, ¬ß3 has two parts called ¬ß4 and ¬ß5. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: So ¬ß6 is ¬ß7? Why ¬ß8?\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: ¬ß9 refers to *modus ponens*. *Modus ponens* is a figure of "
"reasoning dating back to antiquity, which is used in many logical systems ‚Ä¶ "
"whatever. The ‚Äúr‚ÄĚ in ¬ß10 is for ‚Äúreverse‚ÄĚ, of course."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L06_Iff
msgid "Intro Implis L06"
msgstr ""
"**Head of Operations**: We used to have a few conveyor belts that could run "
"in both directions. I had them all shut down as a precaution because the "
"latest manuals advise against using such double belts. But perhaps it's safe "
"to use them under certain conditions? What do you think about this scenario?"

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L06_Iff
msgid "Parts available in assumptions"
msgstr "**You**: Ah, and I already have both parts in the assumptions."

#. ¬ß0: `A ‚ÜĒ B`
#. ¬ß1: $A \\iff B$
#. ¬ß2: `A ‚ÜĒ B`
#. ¬ß3: `‚ü®A ‚Üí B, B ‚Üí A‚ü©`
#. ¬ß4: `A ‚ąß B`
#. ¬ß5: `constructor`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L06_Iff
msgid ""
"¬ß0 is Leanic for ¬ß1. ¬ß2 consists of two parts. It is defined as ¬ß3.\n"
"It is a similar defintion to ¬ß4. Start with ¬ß5"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: ¬ß0 is, of course, Leanish for ¬ß1, i.e. for ‚Äúif and only if‚ÄĚ. "
"The statement ¬ß2 therefore has two parts ‚Äď it is defined as ¬ß3. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Similar to AND, ¬ß4? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Exactly. So you can also start with ¬ß5 here."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L07_Symm
msgid "Conclusion Implis L07"
msgstr ""
"**Head of Operations**: Indeed, that was simple. But the next problem looks "
"more difficult."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L07_Symm
msgid "Intro Implis L07"
msgstr "**Head of Operations**: Here's something else."

