"Intro Implis L14: This chapter used the following operations:\n"
"¬ß0, ¬ß1, ¬ß2, ¬ß3 (reversal of ¬ß4), ¬ß5, ¬ß6, ¬ß7 (changes ¬ß8 to ¬ß9),\n"
"¬ß10 (changes ¬ß11 to ¬ß12 and ¬ß13), ¬ß14 (rewrite goal with ¬ß15), ¬ß16 (rewrite\n"
"assumption ¬ß17 using ¬ß18) and ¬ß19 (introduce cases ¬ß20 and ¬ß21)"
msgstr ""
"**Head of Operations**: You've really helped me out! Here's the last "
"problem. I inherited this from my predecessor. He claimed that if we could "
"solve this, everything would be back on track. But it always seemed far too "
"difficult for me to even try. Would you like to give it a go?\n"
"\n"
"**You**: Sure, let's have a look at it! Scribble, could you perhaps show me "
"another nice summary of what I've learned in the last five minutes? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Here it is: \n"
"\n"
"## Notation\n"
"\n"
"| | Description |\n"
"|:--- |:---------------------------- | \n"
"| ¬ß0 | Implication | \n"
"| ¬ß1 | exactly-when / equivalence | \n"
"\n"
"## Tactics \n"
"\n"
"| Tactic | Example | \n"
"|:---------------- "
"|:----------------------------------------------------------------- | \n"
"| ¬ß2 | moves the left side of an implication in the goal into the "
"assumptions |\n"
"| ¬ß3 | reversal of ¬ß4 | \n"
"| ¬ß5 | applies implication ‚Äúbackwards‚ÄĚ to the goal | \n"
"| ¬ß6 | applies implication ‚Äúforwards‚ÄĚ to an assumption | \n"
"| ¬ß7 | changes ¬ß8 to ¬ß9 |\n"
"| ¬ß10 | changes ¬ß11 to ¬ß12 and ¬ß13 | \n"
"| ¬ß14 | rewrites goal using equivalence ¬ß15 | \n"
"| ¬ß16 | rewrites assumption ¬ß17 using equivalence ¬ß18 | \n"
"| ¬ß19 | case distinction between ¬ß20 and ¬ß21 |"

#. ¬ß0: `by_cases`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L14_Summary
msgid "Maybe try ¬ß0 again"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Perhaps you could use ¬ß0 again."

#. ¬ß0: `‚Üí`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L14_Summary
msgid "Remind that ¬ß0 in this case is equivalence"
msgstr ""
"**You** *(whispering)*: Isn't that the definition of ¬ß0? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble** *(whispering)*: You could see it that way. But in Leanish, "
"these two are  equivalence."

#. ¬ß0: `h`
#. ¬ß1: `obtain`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L14_Summary
msgid "To divide assumption ¬ß0 use ¬ß1"
msgstr "**Scribble**: I would split the assumption ¬ß0 with ¬ß1."

#. ¬ß0: `intro`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L14_Summary
msgid "Try ¬ß0 to solve implication"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Well, you always start with ¬ß0 when it comes to implications."

#. ¬ß0: `tauto`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L14_Summary
msgid "[Doc.Theorem] ¬ß0 can be used instead"
msgstr "Logical statements like this can also be proved with ¬ß0."

#: Game.Levels.Iso
msgid "Intro Iso"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Look, another planet with two skyscrapers! \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes, but these ones are the same height. Now I really don't "
"know where to land. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: People are waving on the left! \n"
"\n"
"So you land on the left. But the reception is rather poor.\n"
"\n"
"**Isosopher**: Excuse me! But it's not very polite to land here in the "
"middle of a crowd! We specifically marked a landing site over there! \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: So sorry! I didn't recognise the markup. \n"
"\n"
"**Isosopher**: Well, at least no one gut hurt. We'd already heard that you "
"were a little ‚Ä¶ different. And we're very keen to show you our ingenious "
"transport system ‚Äď the most advanced local transport system in the entire "
"Leaniverse! \n"
"\n"
"As it turns out, the particularly advanced aspect of their system is that "
"the capsules can be used in both directions. You dash back and forth a few "
"times."

#: Game.Levels.Iso
msgid "Iso"
msgstr "Iso"

#: Game.Levels.Iso.L01_Bijective
msgid "Conclusion Iso L01"
msgstr ""
"**Isosopher**: Great! In that case, I think we can skip all of this ‚Ä¶ He "
"puts a few sheets of paper aside."

#: Game.Levels.Iso.L01_Bijective
msgid "Intro Iso L01"
msgstr "**Isososoph**: Of course we have also prepared something for you."

#. ¬ß0: `Bijective f`
#. ¬ß1: `Injective f ‚ąß Surjective f`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L01_Bijective
msgid "Remind that ¬ß0 is defined as ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble** *(whispering)*: ¬ß0 is defined as ¬ß1. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Then this is easy!"

#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Conclusion Iso L02"
msgstr ""
"The isosophers seem very satisfied indeed. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Could we ‚Ä¶ capsulate once more now? \n"
"\n"
"**Isosopher**: Sure! But only one person at a time. \n"
"Since we started using the capsules in both directions, accidents have been "
"on the rise again. \n"
"\n"
"Scribble makes three more round trips. Then you can continue your journey."

#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Disect again"
msgstr "**Scribble**: And the AND!"

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{h}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Disect ¬ß0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Break down ¬ß0 as far as you can!"

#. ¬ß0: `Bijective`
#. ¬ß1: `obtain ‚ü®hinj, hsurj‚ü©  := ¬ę{h}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `Injective`
#. ¬ß3: `Surjective`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid ""
"Divide ¬ß0 via ¬ß1 into\n"
"¬ß2 and ¬ß3"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Why don't you first split ¬ß0 into ¬ß2 and ¬ß3 with ¬ß1?"

#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Intro Iso L02"
msgstr "**Isosopher**: ‚Ä¶ and immediately move on to the main problem."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{g}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{f}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `have hR : RightInverse ¬ę{g}¬Ľ ¬ę{f}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Show that ¬ß0 is right inverse to ¬ß1 e.g. ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Why don't you first show that ¬ß0 is a right inverse of ¬ß1?  "
"You could start with: ¬ß2."

#. ¬ß0: `simp [LeftInverse]`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Simplify goal with ¬ß0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: With ¬ß0, you can simplify the goal somewhat."

#. ¬ß0: `y : B`
#. ¬ß1: `x : A`
#. ¬ß2: `choose`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid ""
"Surjectivity states that each ¬ß0 possesses a preimage ¬ß1.\n"
"Try to construct a inverse mapping via ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: From surjectivity, you know that every ¬ß0 has a preimage ¬ß1. "
"Can't you use this to construct an inverse map with ¬ß2?"

#. ¬ß0: `intro`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Try beginning with ¬ß0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Why don't you start with ¬ß0?"

#. ¬ß0: `f a = f b`
#. ¬ß1: `g (f a) = g (f b)`
#. ¬ß2: `f a = f b`
#. ¬ß3: `rw`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid ""
"Try to state that if ¬ß0 then also ¬ß1.\n"
"When ¬ß2 available use ¬ß3."
msgstr ""
"**You**: If the arguments ¬ß0 are the same, then also ¬ß1 ‚Äď how do I formulate "
"this here? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Well, if you have ¬ß2, you can just use ¬ß3."

#. ¬ß0: `intro`
#. ¬ß1: `ISO_SECOND`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Try ¬ß0 to approach injectivity ¬ß1"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Injectivity is the more difficult part. Start with ¬ß0."

#. ¬ß0: `RightInverse`
#. ¬ß1: `rw`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "Use assumption ¬ß0 with ¬ß1"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Here you can use the ¬ß0 assumption with ¬ß1."

#. ¬ß0: `IN_HINT 1`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid "¬ß0 stroy"
msgstr ""
"**You**: A map is bijective if and only if it has an inverse. \n"
"That is essentially what we already showed on Epo and on Mono. \n"
"Did you bring along those proofs?\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes. But I think unpacking them here will raise eyebrows. \n"
"Let's rather reproduce them step by step."

#: Game.Levels.Logo
msgid "Intro Logo"
msgstr ""
"Due to an unforeseen and non-canonical singularity in space-time, you have "
"accidentally stumbled into a parallel universe. It appears there is no going "
"back. You had better prepare yourself to stay and find your way around. \n"
"\n"
"There are lots of friendly little planets orbiting around. All habitable, "
"and with up to seven sunsets a day included.\n"
"However, they are inhabited by formalosophers, strange creatures with "
"unorthodox mathematical obsessions. To make things worth, word has already "
"spread that you were a mathematician in your previous universe. You will "
"find no peace here until you learn how to satisfy their insatiable thirst "
"for knowledge.\n"
"\n"
"There are two minor complications: firstly, the formalosophers appear to "
"have no deeper understanding of mathematics whatsoever, and secondly, they "
"communicate about mathematics exclusively in Leanish, a dialect that is "
"completely foreign to you. \n"
"\n"
"Fortunately, Scribble has changed universes with you. Scribble is your "
"little smart-elf. He may not be the mathematical genius you would have "
"wished for in this situation, but it seems he already knows some Leanish "
"from somewhere. And knowing some Leanish is a game changer in this place."

#: Game.Levels.Logo
msgid "Logo"
msgstr "Logo"

#. ¬ß0: `tauto`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L01_Tauto
msgid "Conclusion Logo L01: Remind that ¬ß0 cannot be used"
msgstr ""
"**Logwynn** *(somewhat taken aback)*:  Yes, strictly speaking, that is "
"correct. But don't believe for one moment that this will get you very far on "
"*this* planet! My subjects do not comprehend ¬ß0. You will have to try a "
"little harder than that."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ ¬ę{B}¬Ľ ¬ę{C}¬Ľ : Prop`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß3: `¬ę{C}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß4: `‚Üí`
#. ¬ß5: $‚áí$
#. ¬ß6: `tauto`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L01_Tauto
msgid ""
"Explain that ¬ß0 introduces statements ¬ß1, ¬ß2 und ¬ß3 as\n"
"propositions. The symbol ¬ß4 is equivalent to the implication symbol ¬ß5. Try "
"¬ß6."
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: It's quite simple. \n"
"By ¬ß0, she means: ¬ß1, ¬ß2 and ¬ß3 are arbitrary statements (or "
"*prop*ositions). \n"
"And by ¬ß4, she means ¬ß5, i.e. ‚Äúimplies‚ÄĚ. \n"
"You know the other symbols, don't you? \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Um, yes. But I still need to think about it.\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble** *(whispering)*: Just claim it's a tautology. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Seriously? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes. Just write ¬ß6. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Come on ‚Ä¶"

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L01_Tauto
msgid "Intro Logo L01"
msgstr ""
"Right now, you're on Queen Logwynn's planet. She gets straight to the "
"point:\n"
"\n"
"**Logwynn**: Honourable beings from a world unknown to us, welcome to the "
"Leaniverse!  May I ask just one question?  Why is it that ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"And she scribbles something on a piece of paper: a few assumptions at the "
"top, a conclusion at the bottom. In between, you are apparently supposed to "
"write down a proof. You turn to Scribble with a helpless expression."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L02_Rfl
msgid "Conclusion Logo L02"
msgstr ""
"**Subject**: Ah, right. Yes, you're absolutely right. I keep forgetting. "
"Rfl, rfl, rfl ‚Ä¶"

#. ¬ß0: $42 = 42$
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L02_Rfl
msgid "Intro Logo L02: Why is ¬ß0?"
msgstr ""
"In the meantime, a long queue of subjects has formed, all eager to ask their "
"questions. Logwynn beckons the first one forward. He clears his throat. \n"
"\n"
"\n"
"**Subject**: Why is ¬ß0? \n"
"\n"
"You look at him in disbelief. He writes it down for you."

#. ¬ß0: `rfl`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L02_Rfl
msgid "Remind: Equality is reflexive, so try ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: But this is obvious. You just have to remind him that equality "
"is *reflexive*. Try ¬ß0."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L03_Assumption
msgid "Conclusion Logo L03"
msgstr ""
"**Subject**: Yes, that's right! If only you knew how much I've racked my "
"brains over this question!"

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{n}¬Ľ : ‚Ąē`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{n}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `¬ę{n}¬Ľ ‚ąą ‚Ąē`
#. ¬ß3: `¬ę{h‚āĀ}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß4: `¬ę{h‚āā}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß5: `¬ę{h‚āÉ}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß6: `n < 10`
#. ¬ß7: `1 < n`
#. ¬ß8: `n ‚Č† 5`
#. ¬ß9: `1 < n`
#. ¬ß10: `assumption`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L03_Assumption
msgid ""
"Explain that ¬ß0 means ¬ß1 is a natural number. The notation ¬ß2 is not used.\n"
"¬ß3, ¬ß4, ¬ß5 are names for the respective assumptions ¬ß6, ¬ß7 und ¬ß8.\n"
"The proof goal is ¬ß9. Try ¬ß10"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: ¬ß0 means ¬ß1 is a natural number. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Then why doesn't he write ¬ß2? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Because he's a strange type ‚Ä¶ I can try to explain it later, "
"if you like. Right now, I just want to decipher the question.\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: So, ¬ß3, ¬ß4, ¬ß5 are just names for different assumptions, "
"namely for assumptions the ¬ß6, ¬ß7 and ¬ß8. We have to prove: ¬ß9. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: But that is precisely one of the assumptions. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: True.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: ??? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: You just have say so. Try ¬ß10."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L03_Assumption
msgid "Intro Logo L03"
msgstr ""
"While the first subject is still murmuring rfl, rfl, rfl, the next one steps "
"forward. He is shy and communicates only in writing."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L04_Assumption
msgid "Conclusion Logo L04"
msgstr "**Subject**: That was quick. Great! Thank you very much."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ : Prop`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `¬ę{hA}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß3: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß4: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L04_Assumption
msgid ""
"Explain that ¬ß0 means that ¬ß1 is some statement.\n"
"¬ß2 is the name of the assumption that ¬ß3 is true. Try to solve ¬ß4 using said "
"assumption"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Here, ¬ß0 again means that ¬ß1 is some kind of statement. And ¬ß2 "
"is a name for the assumption that ¬ß3 is true. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: And based on this assumption, we are now supposed to prove ¬ß4? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes. You can figure this one out yourself, can't you?"

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L04_Assumption
msgid "Intro Logo L04"
msgstr "A third subject approaches you with the following problem."

#. ¬ß0: `assumption`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L04_Assumption
msgid "Use ¬ß0 as goal is in assumptions"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: It's just like before: the statement that needs to be proven "
"is already one of the assumptions. So ¬ß0 will work again."

#. ¬ß0: `decide`
#. ¬ß1: `decide`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L05_True
msgid ""
"Conclusion Logo L05: ¬ß0 cannot be used every time. ¬ß1 works only in special "
"cases"
msgstr ""
"**Rascal**: Just wanted to check you aren't fools ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"**You** *(to Scribble)*: Can't we just always use this ¬ß0? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, ¬ß1 only works in special situations where an algorithm is "
"known that can decide whether the statement is true."

#. ¬ß0: `True`
#. ¬ß1: `decide`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L05_True
msgid "Explain that ¬ß0 is a special statement that is always true. Try ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: This ¬ß0 is a very special statement, namely the statement that "
"is always and unconditionally true. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: So what exactly remains to be done here? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: ¬ß1dly little."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L05_True
msgid "Intro Logo L05"
msgstr "The next subject in the queue is a rascal."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L06_Not
msgid "Conclusion Logo L06"
msgstr "The sister laughs, then rushes off to catch up with her brother."

#. ¬ß0: `¬¨`
#. ¬ß1: `(A : Prop)`
#. ¬ß2: `¬¨A`
#. ¬ß3: `False`
#. ¬ß4: `decide`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L06_Not
msgid ""
"Explain that ¬ß0 is the negation sign. If ¬ß1 is true than ¬ß2 is false and\n"
"vica versa. ¬ß3 is the statement that is always false. Try ¬ß4"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: This symbol ¬ß0 means negation. If ¬ß1 is true, then ¬ß2 is "
"false, and vice versa. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: And ¬ß3 is probably the statement that is always false? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: True. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: So can't I use ¬ß4 again? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Perhaps."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L06_Not
msgid "Intro Logo L06"
msgstr "The rascal has brought his sister along."

#. ¬ß0: `contradiction`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L07_Contradiction
msgid "Conclusion Logo L07: There is ¬ß0 in assumptions"
msgstr ""
"The first troublemaker seems satisfied. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Was that a proof by contradiction? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, no, not at all.  A proof by contradiction looks different. "
"The argument here was: we have a ¬ß0 in our assumptions, from which any "
"statement follows."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{h}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `False`
#. ¬ß3: `False`
#. ¬ß4: `False`
#. ¬ß5: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß6: `True`
#. ¬ß7: `False`
#. ¬ß8: `contradiction`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L07_Contradiction
msgid ""
"Explain that ¬ß0 is a statement and ¬ß1 is the assumption that ¬ß2 is true.\n"
"Remind that ¬ß3 is always false. Explain that assumption ¬ß4 is false. As any "
"statement\n"
"¬ß5 can be proven from a false assumption. Point out contradiction between ¬ß6 "
"and ¬ß7\n"
"by applying ¬ß8."
msgstr ""
"**You**: If I'm reading this correctly, ¬ß0 is a statement, and we also have "
"an assumption called ¬ß1, which says ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: ‚Ä¶ which says that ¬ß2 is true. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: I thought ¬ß3 is never true. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**:  Exactly. The assumption ¬ß4 is plainly false. And as you know, "
"you can prove anything starting from a false assumption! In particular, you "
"can prove the statement we are looking for, ¬ß5. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: And how do I explain this to our formalosopher? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: I think you need to point out to him that there is a "
"contradiction between the generally accepted belief ¬ß6 and his assumption "
"¬ß7. Try ¬ß8."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L07_Contradiction
msgid "Intro Logo L07"
msgstr ""
"Next up are three troublemakers. The first one has the following problem:"

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{n}¬Ľ ‚Č† ¬ę{n}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L08_Contradiction
msgid "Check that ¬ß0 is contradiction by the Contradiction tactic"
msgstr ""
"**You** Isn't ¬ß0 also a contradiction? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Perhaps ‚Ä¶?"

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L08_Contradiction
msgid "Conclusion Logo L08"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Yes, this seems to have worked.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: But somehow this still seems a little suspicious to me. Haven't I "
"just proven that every natural number is equal to 37? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, of course not. Only every natural number that is not equal "
"to itself is equal to 37. It's also equal to 38, and to 39, ‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Okay, okay, I understand."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L08_Contradiction
msgid "Intro Logo L08"
msgstr "Enter second troublemaker."

#. ¬ß0: `n ‚Č† 10`
#. ¬ß1: `n = 10`
#. ¬ß2: `‚Č†`
#. ¬ß3: `¬¨(¬∑ = ¬∑)`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L09_Contradiction
msgid "Conclusion Logo L09: ¬ß0 is negation of ¬ß1. ¬ß2 has to be read as ¬ß3"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Well done! I guess in this question, the contradiction is a "
"little more obvious: assumption ¬ß0 is precisely the negation of ¬ß1. You "
"always need to read ¬ß2 as ¬ß3."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L09_Contradiction
msgid "Intro Logo L09"
msgstr "Enter the third troublemaker."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L09_Contradiction
msgid "Try the Contradiction tactic"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Another contradiction in the assumptions?\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: You're getting the hang of it."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L10_And
msgid "Conclusion Logo L10"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Great! \n"
"\n"
"He seems to be enjoying these questions now. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Do you think this lever marked ‚ÄúEditor mode‚ÄĚ is real? Or is it "
"just a mock-up? Can you try?"

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß2: `¬ę{A}¬Ľ und ¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß3: `trivial`
#. ¬ß4: `constructor`
#. ¬ß5: `destructor`
#. ¬ß6: `constructor`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L10_And
msgid ""
"Given assumptions that ¬ß0 and ¬ß1 are true, prove that ¬ß2 is true.\n"
"You cannot just try ¬ß3. Use ¬ß4 to divide goal into two. Remind that the "
"tactic\n"
"is not called ¬ß5. Try ¬ß6"
msgstr ""
"**You**: So, we have two assumptions: ¬ß0 is true, and ¬ß1 is also true. And "
"they want us to prove ¬ß2. These formal fanatics are crazy. Can't I just say "
"¬ß3 again? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, that won't work this time. You'll have to break the goal "
"into two parts. Try ¬ß4.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: You mean ¬ß5? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, ¬ß6. I know it's confusing, but that's what they call it "
"here."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L10_And
msgid "Intro Logo L10"
msgstr ""
"The next formalosopher in the queue has brought a question with him. He "
"presents it to us, sits down and starts knitting."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L10_And
msgid "Now there is goal ¬ß0. This goal is part of the assumption"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Look, this is magic paper. Now we suddenly have two goals. "
"Here is goal ¬ß0. I think you already know how to achieve each of them. The "
"targets are listed in the *assumptions*."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L10_And
