#. ¬ß4: `Fin 2`
#. ¬ß5: $\\{0,1\\}$
#. ¬ß6: `X 0`
#. ¬ß7: `X 1`
#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L03_mul_comm
msgid ""
"Explain ¬ß0: ¬ß1 is a 'multivariate polynome' with variables indexed by ¬ß2 "
"and\n"
"coefficients in ¬ß3.\n"
"Explain ¬ß4 as the set of elements ¬ß5 that lead to the variables ¬ß6 and ¬ß7"
msgstr ""
"**You**: What's this here? What kind of creature is ¬ß0? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: ¬ß1 is a ‚Äúmultivariate polynomial‚ÄĚ, where the variables are "
"numbered consecutively with ¬ß2 and the coefficients are in ¬ß3.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: And what is ¬ß4? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: The standard set with two elements ‚Äď ¬ß5. So the variables are "
"called ¬ß6 and ¬ß7. \n"
"\n"
"**You**:  But none of that really matters here, does it? After all, the "
"polynomial ring is commutative! \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: That's right."

#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L03_mul_comm
msgid "Intro Saturn L03"
msgstr "Another radio message."

#. ¬ß0: `‚Ąē`
#. ¬ß1: `‚Ąē`
#. ¬ß2: `ring`
#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L04_mul_assoc
msgid ""
"Conclusion Saturn L04: coefficients were in ¬ß0. Polynomes with coefficients "
"in ¬ß1\n"
"are not considered rings. ¬ß2 does also work on half rings."
msgstr ""
"Another ūüĎć. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: But wait a minute, this time the coefficients were in ¬ß0! That's "
"not a ring at all, and polynomials with coefficients in ¬ß1 don't form a ring "
"either. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Maybe not. But ¬ß2 even works in so-called semi-rings.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: I see ‚Ä¶\n"
"\n"
"The anonymous radio source inquires whether you're ready for the end game, "
"or if you'd rather orbit the planet a few more times. Scribble's answer is "
"short and clear: ‚ÄúReady‚ÄĚ."

#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L04_mul_assoc
msgid "Intro Saturn L04"
msgstr "Another radio message."

#. ¬ß0: `mul_assoc`
#. ¬ß1: `ring`
#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L04_mul_assoc
msgid "Try ¬ß0 or again ¬ß1"
msgstr "**Scribble**: You could use ¬ß0 here. Or ¬ß1 *again* ‚Ä¶"

#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L05_Ring
msgid "Conclusion Saturn L05"
msgstr ""
"‚ÄúPass‚ÄĚ says the anonymous radio operator succinctly. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: I think the engine has sufficiently regenerated by now. Let's "
"get out of here!"

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza
msgid "Intro Spinoza"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: I think that's Spinoza, one of the very few asteroids of the "
"QED type. Quick. We have to hurry a bit, otherwise we'll miss it. \n"
"\n"
"Half an hour later, you've landed. Spinoza doesn't look very inviting. Its "
"entire surface is covered with fine, red dust. A single, lonely "
"formalosopher, who introduces himself as Benedictus, is waiting for you.\n"
"\n"
"**Benedictus**: Glad to see you! I've been waiting for you! \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Do you also have some urgent questions ‚Ä¶? \n"
"\n"
"**Benedictus**: Oh no, I'm past that age. But I can imagine what it was like "
"on Implis and Quantus. And believe me, it's not much better on the other "
"planets. But perhaps I can prepare you a little. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Can't we just stay here and rest a while? \n"
"\n"
"Benedictus shakes his head. \n"
"\n"
"**Benedictus**: No. Spinoza cannot accommodate three inhabitants. And you "
"must continue your journey soon, otherwise the return journey will become "
"impossibly long. We only pass by the planets every 400 years or so."

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza
msgid "Spinoza"
msgstr "Spinoza"

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L01_Have
msgid "Conclusion Spinoza L01"
msgstr "**Benedictus**: That looks good!"

#. ¬ß0: `contradiction`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L01_Have
msgid "If to assumptions contradict each other use ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**You**: How did I say that two assumptions contradict each other? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: ¬ß0."

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L01_Have
msgid "Intro Spinoza L01"
msgstr "**Benedictus**: Here, take a look. I have prepared something for you."

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L01_Have
msgid "Prove the assumption before using it"
msgstr ""
"**You**: What? I can just assume it's true?\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, of course not. You now need to prove it before you can use "
"it."

#. ¬ß0: `‚ąß`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L01_Have
