msgstr "**You**: So, first of all, I suppose I'll split And (¬ß0)."

#. ¬ß0: `have`
#. ¬ß1: `have g : ¬¨ B`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L01_Have
msgid "Try ¬ß0 in form of ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**You**: And now‚Ä¶ \n"
"\n"
"**Benedictus**: ‚Ä¶you should come up with a suitable intermediate result. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes! Try ¬ß0 again. Or more precisely: ¬ß1!"

#. ¬ß0: `apply`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L01_Have
msgid "¬ß0 should help"
msgstr "**Scribble**: ¬ß0 should help."

#. ¬ß0: `have`
#. ¬ß1: `suffices`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L02_Suffices
msgid ""
"Conclusion Spinoza L02: The use of ¬ß0 or ¬ß1 is up to personal preference."
msgstr ""
"**Benedictus**: That's exactly what I meant. Whether you use ¬ß0 or ¬ß1 in "
"future is purely a matter of taste. The main thing is that you know how to "
"reach distant goals in small steps."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{g}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L02_Suffices
msgid "End proof with assumption that ¬ß0 is true"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: So here you can conclude the proof assuming that ¬ß0 is true."

#. ¬ß0: `have`
#. ¬ß1: `suffices`
#. ¬ß2: `suffices g : ¬¨B`
#. ¬ß3: `g`
#. ¬ß4: `g`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L02_Suffices
msgid ""
"Instead of ¬ß0, ¬ß1 can be used. After ¬ß2, you have to show how to\n"
"prove goal by ¬ß3 before proving ¬ß4 itself."
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: I know what he means! Instead of ¬ß0, you can also use ¬ß1. It "
"works exactly the same, except that the two proof goals are reversed. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: So after ¬ß2, I first have to show how to complete the proof with ¬ß3 "
"before I prove ¬ß4? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Exactly!"

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L02_Suffices
msgid "Intro Spinoza L02"
msgstr ""
"**Benedictus**: Of course, you could also have proven the main result first, "
"and then the intermediate result afterwords. You can try this alternative "
"with this problem, which is very similar."

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L02_Suffices
msgid "Prove intermediate result"
msgstr "**Scribble**: And now you prove the intermediate result."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{h}¬Ľ : ¬ę{A}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `suffices`
#. ¬ß2: `suffices k : B`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L03_ByContra
msgid "Apply contradiction with ¬ß0 via ¬ß1 with ¬ß2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: So now you have an assumption ¬ß0, and you have to derive a "
"contradiction from it. \n"
"\n"
"For example, you could now use ¬ß1 to say which contradiction you would like "
