"\n"
"**You**: And how do I do that? With ¬ß1? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, you start with ¬ß2 ‚Äď ¬ß3 only comes at the very end."

#. ¬ß0: `¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#. ¬ß1: `¬¨¬ę{B}¬Ľ`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L03_ByContra
msgid "Finish proof by stating contradiction between ¬ß0 and ¬ß1"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Ah, and now I can simply note that assumptions ¬ß0 and ¬ß1 contradict "
"each other."

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L03_ByContra
msgid "Intro Spinoza L03"
msgstr "**Benedictus**: Here's another variation."

#. ¬ß0: `not_imp_not`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L04_ByContra
msgid "Intro Spinoza L04: introduce contraposition equivalence with ¬ß0"
msgstr ""
"**Benedictus**: I have another interesting question about odd squares for "
"you. But first, you'd better prove this equivalence here. I think you might "
"even have a name for it: *equivalence of contrapositives*, or something like "
"that. In Leanish, we simply say ¬ß0. A much more obvious name, don't you "
"think?"

#. ¬ß0: $A ‚áí B$
#. ¬ß1: $¬¨B ‚áí ¬¨A$
#. ¬ß2: `not_imp_not`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L04_ByContra
msgid "Often to prove ¬ß0, ¬ß1 can be proven as well. Here this is called ¬ß2."
msgstr ""
"**You**: Yes, I have indeed seen this before. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Of course you have. Mathematicians use it all the time. If "
